author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Embera elders often blame malevolent spirits for the deaths of young people, having no word for suicide in their language. Ilsa Banuvi, who was raised between Indigenous tradition and modern society, spearheads organisations that seek to reinforce identity while also recognising the need to adapt.

Journeying from Quibdo city deep into the Choco jungle, Ilsa examines many challenges the Embera are confronted by and why young women are disproportionately affected. As she takes on culturally sensitive action, a football championship for Indigenous girls offers hope of unity for often isolated communities. But can Ilsa navigate the often paradoxical perspectives and help her people?

Suicide in the Jungle is a documentary film by Bruno Federico and Simone Bruno.

#aljazeeraenglish #documentary #AJWitness #Colombia #Indigenous
title: A silent crisis in Colombia’s Indigenous Embera community | Witness Documentary

Children today grow up surrounded by screens, swipes and algorithm-driven content. While digital life connects, educates and entertains, it can also distract, misinforms and reshape identity. But is social media helping young people or harming them?

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Palestinian farmers in Gaza are returning to their devastated fields despite lacking equipment and seedlings.
Vast areas once filled with crops now lie barren after the war wiped out orchards, vegetables and greenhouses.
Agriculture previously made up 10 percent of Gaza’s economy, but 80 percent of farmland and 71 percent of the greenhouses are now damaged.
Only a small fraction of land remains usable, forcing farmers to start again from almost nothing.
Many, like Ahmed Abu Hallima, are replanting as an act of livelihood and resilience after displacement.
Each seed represents work, dignity and recovery in a landscape stripped of its foundations.
Gaza’s farmers are rebuilding a lifeline the war nearly erased.

Al Jazeera’s Ibrahim al-Khalili reports from Gaza City.  
Bahaa Zakout is the director of External Relations and Fundraising at the Palestinian Agricultural Development Association. He joins us from Deir Al Balah to discuss the latest developments.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Shaina Low of the Norwegian Refugee Council told Al Jazeera that Gaza’s recent storms have been “horrific”, flooding thousands of tents and destroying the few belongings displaced families have left.
She said shortages of shelter materials persist because Israel is blocking NRC and other NGOs from bringing in aid stored in Egypt, despite their valid registrations.
Low explained that low-lying displacement sites need drainage channels and heavy machinery, but such equipment is also being denied entry.
She noted that the shelter cluster, which NRC co-leads, coordinates with the UN and NGOs to distribute shelter supplies equitably.
However, limited space, severe destruction, unexploded ordnance and aid restrictions all hamper the response.
Low stressed that proper tents and materials must meet humanitarian standards, pointing to tents collapsing under rain.
She urged immediate approval for machinery, demining teams and essential shelter items to enter Gaza.

description:
South Africa says it will no longer accept evacuation flights bringing Palestinians from Gaza and the occupied West Bank.
The foreign minister argues the flights are part of a broader plan to depopulate Palestinian territories.

They expressed uncertainty about their future and fear for relatives still trapped in Gaza.

The UK Home Secretary Shabana Mahmood has laid out the country's most significant asylum policy reforms in decades.

The changes are modelled on the Danish system and aim to make the journey less attractive to undocumented migrants. 

Al Jazeera’s Rory Challands reports from Dover, in southern England.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
US President Donald Trump has reversed his position and told Republican lawmakers to vote for the release of the controversial Epstein files.
It follows weeks of presidential criticism for those planning to force the release, with Trump claiming he was the victim of a Democratic Hoax. 
Jeffrey Epstein, a former friend of Trump’s, was found dead in his prison cell in 2019, while awaiting trial for child sex trafficking.
Trump says if a bill to release the documents is passed by Congress, he will sign it into law.
But the files may never see the light of day, even if they’re approved.
The president’s remarks also come amid an unusually public rupture with parts of his political base, including a highly visible split with Georgia Representative Marjorie Taylor Greene, once among his closest allies.
Trump has since distanced himself from Greene, saying he would endorse a challenger to her in next year’s midterm elections “if the right person runs”.

Al Jazeera’s Alan Fisher reports from W
title: Trump backs full release of Epstein files in sharp reversal

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The United Nations Security Council has approved a resolution mandating a transitional administration and an International Stabilisation Force in Gaza that envisions a “credible pathway” to Palestinian statehood.
The resolution, drafted by the United States as part of President Donald Trump’s 20-point peace plan, passed in a 13-0 vote on Monday, paving the way for the crucial next steps for the fragile ceasefire between Israel and Hamas. Russia and China abstained from the vote.
Arab and other Muslim countries that expressed interest in providing troops for an international force had previously indicated that a UN mandate was essential for their participation. At their behest, the US had included more defined language about Palestinian self-determination in the draft to get it over the finish line.

Al Jazeera’s Gabriel Elizondo reports from the United Nations.
